ARZAI became the first democratically elected president of Afghanistan and the National Assembly was inaugurated the following December. KARZAI was re-elected in August 2009 for a second term. Despite gains toward building a stable central government, a resurgent Taliban and continuing provincial instability - particularly in the south and the east - remain serious challenges for the Afghan Government.', 'Islamic Republic of Afghanistan', 800, 20920000000, 33.0, 'N', 'Southern Asia, north and west of Pakistan, east of Iran', 65.0, 'E', 'Afghanistan', null);INSERT INTO languages (id, name) VALUES(129, 'Afghan Persian or Dari');INSERT INTO country_languages (country_id, language_id) VALUES(97, 129);INSERT INTO languages (id, name) VALUES(130, 'Pashto');INSERT INTO country_languages (country_id, language_id) VALUES(97, 130);INSERT INTO religions (id, name, value, country_id) VALUES(22, 'Shia Muslim', 19.0, 97);INSERT INTO religions (id, name, value, country_id) VALUES(23, 'Sunni Muslim', 80.0, 97);INSERT INTO religions (id, name, value, country_id) VALUES(24, 'other', 1.0, 97);INSERT INTO cities (id, capital, name, population, country_id) VALUES(97, true, 'KABUL', 3573000, 97);UPDATE countries SET capitol_id=97 WHERE id=97;INSERT INTO countries (id, background, fullName, gdpPerCapita, gdpTotal, latitude, latitudeType, location, longitude, longitudeType, name, capitol_id) VALUES(98, 'Ahmad Shah DURRANI unified the Pashtun tribes and founded Afghanistan in 1747. The country served as a buffer between the British and Russian Empires until it won independence from notional British control in 1919. A brief experiment in democracy ended in a 1973 coup and a 1978 Communist counter-coup. The Soviet Union invaded in 1979 to support the tottering Afghan Communist regime, touching off a long and destructive war. The USSR withdrew in 1989 under relentless pressure by internationally supported anti-Communist mujahedin rebels. A series of subsequent civil wars saw Kabul finally fall